<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="opportunity-solution-trees">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>user-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Visual discovery framework linking outcomes to opportunities, solutions, and experiments. Enforces outcome-first thinking with customer interview evidence anchoring.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
      <tag>product-strategy</tag>
      <tag>research</tag>
      <tag>continuous-discovery</tag>
      <tag>frameworks</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Opportunity Solution Trees</title>
    <summary>A visual discovery framework that links one product outcome to a hierarchy of customer opportunities, candidate solutions, and experiments. The tree enforces outcome-first thinking: no solution may exist without a parent opportunity, and no opportunity is valid without customer-interview evidence.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Teams default to solution-first thinking and skip the opportunity layer, shipping features that pass internally but miss the actual customer need. OST makes the causal chain explicit and auditable — outcome → opportunity → solution → experiment — so teams can prune bad branches before building, not after. Evidence anchoring prevents the tree from becoming a brainstorm dump.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Continuous-discovery cadence (weekly customer touchpoints) where a living artefact connects research to delivery.</item>
        <item>Quarterly planning to translate a north-star outcome into a research-grounded backlog.</item>
        <item>Cross-functional alignment when product, design, and engineering disagree on Solution A vs. B.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new PM/designer to the team's discovery context.</item>
        <item>Refactoring a feature roadmap that has drifted into solution-first thinking.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-discovery: without customer interviews an OST is fiction, not structure.</item>
        <item>Strict waterfall delivery where the backlog is fixed for 6+ months — OST is a discovery tool, not a Gantt.</item>
        <item>Single-experiment hypotheses (one-off A/B test) — overkill; use a hypothesis canvas.</item>
        <item>For OKR setting itself; OST starts with an outcome, it does not generate one.</item>
        <item>Compliance/regulatory work where outcomes are binary (pass/fail) — opportunity branching adds no value.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Node taxonomy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every tree has exactly one Outcome node at the root — a measurable product or business goal with an explicit metric.</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple outcomes in one tree create a hydra: teams cannot prune branches when priorities conflict.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Opportunity nodes must be phrased in customer language describing a problem or unmet need, not a feature or solution.</statement>
        <rationale>Solution-phrased opportunities ("add export button") collapse the discovery process; they skip validation of whether the need exists.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every Opportunity node must carry at least two evidence references (interview IDs, support ticket IDs, or analytics segment IDs) or be marked unvalidated and scheduled for pruning.</statement>
        <rationale>Evidence references are the only signal that distinguishes a real customer need from a brainstorm item.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Solution nodes are mutually exclusive within an opportunity: pick one to test, not all simultaneously.</statement>
        <rationale>Testing multiple solutions at once prevents attribution of results to a specific solution.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Experiment nodes require a written kill criterion (hypothesis, method, success metric, sample size, status). Without a kill criterion, experiments never end.</statement>
        <rationale>Open-ended experiments consume resources indefinitely and produce ambiguous results.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep tree depth at most 4 levels: Outcome → Opportunity → Solution → Experiment.</statement>
        <rationale>Deeper trees indicate scope confusion; the extra levels are almost always sub-opportunities or sub-experiments that should be sibling nodes.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Opportunity vs. solution discipline">
      <rule>
        <statement>A node is an Opportunity if it describes a customer problem in customer language. A node is a Solution if it describes a product response. Run a node-classifier lint before adding any node.</statement>
        <rationale>Teams under delivery pressure reclassify solutions as opportunities to skip validation; a classifier subagent rejects or rewrites ambiguous nodes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Opportunity node: "Add bulk export button"</description>
        <reason>This is a solution, not a customer need. Rewrite as: "Users lose data when browser crashes before they can download."</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Opportunity node: "Users want speed"</description>
        <reason>Too vague to have evidence; cite specific interview IDs or rewrite with a concrete scenario.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Tree as structured data">
      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain the OST as YAML or JSON (not only as a Miro/FigJam diagram) so agents can edit the data and humans review the visual rendering.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents flatten parent-child semantics when editing a diagram directly; the YAML/JSON is the canonical source of truth.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Build and refresh cadence">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a tree review every two weeks: archive validated/dead branches with a date, flag opportunities with no supporting evidence after 30 days.</statement>
        <rationale>Trees grow into unreadable wallpaper without a pruning cadence; stale branches consume planning attention without delivering signal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Connect each experiment to a delivery ticket and an instrumentation plan; without both, the experiment cannot be measured.</statement>
        <rationale>An experiment without instrumentation produces results that cannot be attributed to the intervention.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic workflow and integration">
      <rule>
        <statement>Agents maintain tree hygiene (classify nodes, surface stale branches, cluster duplicate opportunities, generate experiment briefs); discovery decisions stay human.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent-proposed opportunities without evidence IDs are fiction; the agent's role is curation, not ideation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Opportunity extraction from interviews">
        <note>Prompt for opportunity extraction from interviews:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given the OST YAML below and 12 new interview snippets, propose new opportunity
nodes (<=1 sentence each, customer language, no solutions). For each, list the
snippet IDs supporting it. Reject any duplicates of existing opportunities
(cosine similarity >=0.85).]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Solution and experiment generation">
        <note>Prompt for solution and experiment generation:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given opportunity O.users-cant-find-export, generate three candidate solutions
ranging from low to high investment. For each, propose one experiment:
assumption, method, success criterion, sample size, duration.]]></code>
      </example>
      <p>Recommended subagents: A purpose-built ost-curator subagent ingests interview-evidence snippets, attaches them to opportunity nodes, and flags opportunities with no supporting evidence after 30 days. Use brainstorm to diverge on candidate solutions for a chosen opportunity, then converge on top 3 for human review. Use faion-sdd-executor-agent to convert a chosen experiment into a test plan (success metric, sample size, instrumentation). A node-classifier subagent lints proposed nodes for category errors (solution masquerading as opportunity).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent proposes opportunities without evidence IDs ("users want speed").</description>
        <reason>LLMs generate plausible-sounding needs from prior knowledge; require evidence IDs from a known source store before accepting any opportunity node.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent synthesizes experiment outcomes from prior knowledge before evidence is logged.</description>
        <reason>Require explicit "results: TBD" on all experiments until real data is recorded.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent bulk-imports interview snippets without deduplication, flooding the tree with near-identical opportunities.</description>
        <reason>Force a similarity check (cosine >= 0.85 threshold) before adding any evidence or opportunity node.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent overwrites hand-edits in Miro when syncing from YAML.</description>
        <reason>Require optimistic concurrency (etag/version field) on every Miro API write call.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Tree-rendering agents flatten the structure when rendering, losing parent-child semantics.</description>
        <reason>Always serialise from the YAML/JSON, not from the diagram.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Best practices and tools">
      <rule>
        <statement>One outcome per tree; multiple outcomes → multiple trees, never a hydra.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Opportunities phrased in customer language ("I lose my work when…"), not in feature language.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every opportunity has at least two evidence references; otherwise mark as unvalidated and prune.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Solutions are mutually exclusive within an opportunity — pick one to test, not all.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Experiments have a written kill criterion; without one, the experiment never ends.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Re-run a tree review every 2 weeks; archive validated/dead branches with a date.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Connect each experiment to a delivery ticket and an instrumentation plan; otherwise the experiment can't be measured.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep tree depth ≤ 4 levels (outcome → opportunity → solution → experiment); deeper trees indicate scope confusion.</statement>
      </rule>
      <p>CLI tools: Miro REST API renders OST on shared board. FigJam REST API provides alternative render surface. Whimsical API offers lightweight tree boards. Mermaid CLI generates static OST renders in repos and docs. Graphviz dot provides high-density tree rendering for export. gh CLI links experiments to GitHub issues. Linear or Jira CLI syncs experiments to delivery. Dovetail API pulls interview tags as evidence. Notion API serves as source-of-truth tree if not in Miro.</p>
      <p>Services and applications: Miro is the SaaS solution most teams use for OST, with strong REST and webhooks support. FigJam works well for design teams with strong REST API. Whimsical is fast but has weaker API. Mural provides enterprise board control with REST API. Productboard is good for opportunity management at scale with REST API. Dovetail serves as evidence repository to wire under nodes. Notion provides tree-as-database pattern with REST API. Roam Research and Logseq work for personal OST workflows. Tability and Quantive support OKR roll-up at the outcome layer. Linear provides experiment tracking as issues with GraphQL.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Where it fails and limitations">
      <p>Trees grow into wallpaper; without pruning they become unreadable and stale.</p>
      <p>Opportunity ≠ solution discipline collapses under pressure — teams paste features as opportunities ("add export button" is not an opportunity).</p>
      <p>Treating the tree as a Gantt chart kills its discovery purpose; it is a thinking tool, not a delivery plan.</p>
      <p>Without a structured interview cadence, the opportunities tier turns into a brainstorm dump.</p>
      <p>Cross-team trees fragment: each squad runs its own without rolling up to a portfolio outcome.</p>
      <p>Stale branches accumulate when no agent has authority to archive; assign archival to a human owner field on each node.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ost.yaml" purpose="Agent-editable OST schema: outcome, opportunities, solutions, experiments"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.producttalk.org/opportunity-solution-tree/"/>
      <link href="https://www.productboard.com"/>
      <link href="https://miro.com/templates/opportunity-solution-tree/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
